# =============================================================================
# Vite ↔ Django: pick ONE workflow so /api always hits the API you intend.
# =============================================================================
#
# (1) Docker Compose — frontend + API + Postgres together (recommended for team parity)
#     From repo root:  docker compose --profile dev up
#     Or from frontend: npm run docker:dev
#     The Compose file loads frontend/.env.docker (API_PROXY_TARGET=http://web:8000).
#     Do not run a second Vite on the host unless you point it at the same API (see below).
#
# (2) Vite on host + Django on host (manage.py runserver)
#     Default proxy target is http://127.0.0.1:8000 — only one process should listen on 8000.
#     If something else uses 8000, set API_PROXY_TARGET in .env.development.local (or .env), e.g.:
#       API_PROXY_TARGET=http://127.0.0.1:8002
#     vite.config.ts uses Vite loadEnv() so this is applied when you run npm run dev (not only in Docker).
#
# (3) Vite on host + API only in Docker (published port)
#     Example API mapped to host 8000:  API_PROXY_TARGET=http://127.0.0.1:8000
#     Example mapped to 8002:           API_PROXY_TARGET=http://127.0.0.1:8002
#
# (4) Bypass Vite proxy (browser calls Django directly; requires CORS for your Vite origin)
#     VITE_API_BASE=http://127.0.0.1:8000
#
# SEC: contact email for data.sec.gov (also sent as X-Sec-User-Agent-Email on API calls).
#      Can be set in the app UI (localStorage) instead.
# VITE_SEC_USER_AGENT_EMAIL=you@example.com
